Authenticate & Link With Google Drive (For Interactive Sheets)¶

!pip install --upgrade gspread pandas google-auth google-colab

import gspread
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np


from google.colab import auth
from google.auth import default

# Authenticate user
auth.authenticate_user()

# Set up gspread authorization
creds, _ = default()
gc = gspread.authorize(creds)


# Replace with your actual shared Google Sheet ID
spreadsheet_id = '1Is4iHkPOAWx7TiuNIa8ND-OiLkvrwoZ25aXBqrgZuv4'

# Open the Google spreadsheet by ID
spreadsheet = gc.open_by_key(spreadsheet_id)

# Get the worksheet object (e.g., the first sheet)
worksheet = spreadsheet.get_worksheet(0)

# Get all values from the worksheet
data = worksheet.get_all_values()

# Create a Pandas DataFrame
# Assuming the first row contains column headers
df = pd.DataFrame(data[1:], columns=data[0])

# Now you can work with the DataFrame 'df'
print(df)

2. Defining/Loading the Nodes and Edges¶

Define the nodes and edges that characterize the network (as per the chains identified).

Nodes: ~ (true / likely) facts about the world Edges: ~ relationships between facts about the world (e.g. how A causes B and C).

Parse the Adjacency Matrix for Edges¶

In [ ]:
from pgmpy.models import BayesianNetwork

# Initialize an empty list for edges
edges = []

# Parse edges based on non-empty cells in the matrix
for i, source_node in enumerate(nodes_list):
    for j, target_node in enumerate(nodes_list):
        cell_value = edges_matrix[i][j]
        if cell_value:  # If the cell contains text, assume an edge exists
            edges.append((target_node, source_node))  # Directed edge from source to target
print("Extracted edges:", edges)

# Identify self-loop edges
self_loops = [(source, target) for source, target in edges if source == target]
# Filter out self-loop edges
filtered_edges = [(source, target) for source, target in edges if source != target]

# Print the removed self-loops and the filtered edges
print("Self-loops removed:")
for loop in self_loops:
    print(loop)

print("\nFiltered edges (no self-loops):")
for edge in filtered_edges:
    print(edge)

from pyvis.network import Network
import networkx as nx

# Create a NetworkX graph using the filtered edges
nx_graph = nx.DiGraph(filtered_edges)

# Initialize Pyvis Network with cdn_resources set to "in_line"
net = Network(notebook=True, directed=True, cdn_resources="in_line")

# Load the NetworkX graph into Pyvis
net.from_nx(nx_graph)

# Customize layout and physics
net.force_atlas_2based(gravity=-50)
net.show_buttons(filter_=['physics'])

# Display the interactive graph directly in the notebook
net.show("interactive_dag.html")

Display HTML graph in Colab¶

In [ ]:
from pyvis.network import Network
import networkx as nx
from IPython.display import HTML

# Create and configure the graph with Pyvis
nx_graph = nx.DiGraph(filtered_edges)
net = Network(notebook=True, directed=True, cdn_resources="in_line")
net.from_nx(nx_graph)
net.force_atlas_2based(gravity=-50)
net.show_buttons(filter_=['physics'])

# Save the HTML to a file
net.save_graph("interactive_dag.html")

# Read the HTML file contents and embed it directly
with open("interactive_dag.html", "r") as f:

                    values=[[0.95, 0.2],

5. Validating the Model¶

Ensure that the model is correctly specified and the CPDs are consistent.

Ensuring your CPDs are valid is essential for creating a meaningful Bayesian Network. In pgmpy, you can easily check the validity of your defined CPDs using the check_model() method.

Here's how you would do it, continuing from our previous example: model.check_model()

This method will return True if all CPDs are valid and False otherwise.

A valid CPD meets two key criteria:

  1. Probabilities sum to 1: For each combination of parent node values, the probabilities of all possible values for the child node must sum to 1. This ensures a proper probability distribution.
  2. All probabilities are non-negative: No probability value can be less than 0.

If check_model() returns False, you'll need to review your CPD definitions carefully to find and correct any errors.

dangerous It's enough to just define the probabilities; pgmpy will automatically normalize them to ensure validity.

check_circle You must ensure your probability values sum to 1 for each parent node combination; pgmpy will not automatically normalize them.

While pgmpy provides powerful tools, it's your responsibility to define correct probability distributions. The check_model() function helps identify issues but doesn't automatically fix them. Always double-check your CPDs!
